sentences: Alvin Wayne Casey (October 26, 1936 – September 17, 2006) was an American guitarist.
Casey was born in Long Beach, California and moved to Phoenix, Arizona when he was two years old.
By the time he was 14, he was playing the steel guitar for various clubs in Phoenix, and in his later teens he performed five to six nights a week.
By the time he was 14, he was playing the steel guitar for various clubs in Phoenix, and in his later teens he performed five to six nights a week.
In his teens, Casey joined a local group, the Sunset Riders, and worked with vocalist Jody Reynolds.
Around 1956, Casey crossed paths with Lee Hazlewood, a Coolidge, Arizona radio DJ who was looking for a singer to record his song, "The Fool".

Due to the song's success, Casey went on a week long rockabilly tour with Carl Perkins, Gene Vincent, Eddie Cochran, Johnny Burnette, and Sonny James, traveling the country in Sanford Clark's Ford Mercury.
In 1955, Casey met Duane Eddy and joined his band, Duane Eddy and the Rebels.

sentences: For five years, Casey worked on and off with Eddy's band and performed for the Alan Freed and Dick Clark shows.
section: == Career == | === Duane Eddy and the Rebels ===

sentences: Casey wrote one of Eddy's earliest hits, "Ramrod" (1958), and when Eddy performed the song on American Bandstand he was flooded with requests for the single.

sentences: "Ramrod" peaked at No. 27 on the Billboard Hot 100 and No. 17 on the Billboard R&B charts in 1958.

sentences: Casey also co-wrote another Eddy hit, "Forty Miles of Bad Road", which peaked at No. 9 on Billboard's Hot 100 on July 27, 1959.

sentences: In the early 1960s, Casey began working with his own ensemble, the Al Casey Combo.

With this group he scored three instrumental hits: "Cookin" (U.S. No. 92, 1962), "Jivin' Around" (peaked at No. 71 on the Billboard Hot 100 and No. 22 on the Hot R&B/Hip Hop charts in 1962), and "Surfin' Hootenanny" (U.S. #48, 1963).

In 1958, The Arizona Republic noted that Casey performed on 95% of recording sessions held in Phoenix that year.

In 1964, he gave up touring and began to play a variety of music styles for studio sessions.
In 1965, Casey moved to Los Angeles and became part of the group of session musicians which became known as the Wrecking Crew.
He worked with this group for 18 years playing a variety of music styles including jazz, country, rock, and pop.
During this time, Casey also worked for three years as a member of the band on The Dean Martin Show.
In the late 1960s, Casey owned a music store in Hollywood called Al Casey's Music Room.

sentences: Casey continued recording into the 1990s, including an LP release, Sidewinder, for Bear Family Records.
In 2001, he played guitar, dobro, mandolin, and banjo on Al Beasley's A Rainbow in the Clouds album, recorded live at the Kerr Cultural Center in Scottsdale, Arizona.
In 2005, Casey was inducted into the Arizona Music Hall of Fame.
Casey died on September 17, 2006, in Phoenix, Arizona.
In 2008, Casey, along with many of his fellow studio musicians, was featured in the documentary film The Wrecking Crew.
